   and 
  
    
      
        j
      
    
    {\displaystyle j}
  . Most authors define the Vandermonde matrix as the transpose of the above matrix.The determinant of a square Vandermonde matrix (when 
  
    
      
        n
        =
        m
      
    
    {\displaystyle n=m}
  ) is called a Vandermonde determinant or Vandermonde polynomial. Its value is:

  
    
      
        det
        (
        V
        )
        =
        
          ∏
          
            0
            ≤
            i
            <
            j
            ≤
            n
          
        
        (
        
          x
          
            j
          
        
        −
        
          x
          
            i
          
        
        )
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle \det(V)=\prod _{0\leq i<j\leq n}(x_{j}-x_{i}).}
  This is non-zero if and only if all 
  
    
      
        
          x
          
            i
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle x_{i}}
   are distinct (no two are equal), making the Vandermonde matrix invertible.

Applications
The polynomial interpolation problem is to find a polynomial 
  
    
      
