          x
          
            j
          
        
        −
        
          x
          
            i
          
        
        )
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle \det(V)=\prod _{0\leq i<j\leq n}(x_{j}-x_{i}).}

Second proof: linear maps
Let F be a field containing all 
  
    
      
        
          x
          
            i
          
        
        ,
      
    
    {\displaystyle x_{i},}
   and 
  
    
      
        
          P
          
            n
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle P_{n}}
   the F vector space of the polynomials of degree less than or equal to n with coefficients in F. Let 

  
    
      
        φ
        :
        
          P
          
            n
          
        
        →
        
          F
          
            n
            +
            1
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \varphi :P_{n}\to F^{n+1}}
  be the linear map defined by 

  
    
      
        p
        (
        x
        )
        ↦
        (
        p
        (
        
          x
          
            0
          
        
        )
        ,
        p
        (
        
          x
          
            1
          
        
        )
        ,
        …
        ,
        p
        (
        
          x
          
            n
          
        
        )
        )
      
    
    {\displaystyle p(x)\mapsto (p(x_{0}),p(x_{1}),\ldots ,p(x_{n}))}
  .The Vandermonde matrix is the matrix of 
  
    
      
        φ
      
    
    {\displaystyle \varphi }
   with respect to the canonical bases of 
  
    
      
        
          P
          
            n
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle P_{n}}
   and 
  
    
      
        
          F
          
            n
            +
            1
          
        
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle F^{n+1}.}
  
Changing the basis of 
  
    
      
        
          P
          
            n
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle P_{n}}
   amounts to multiplying the Vandermonde matrix by a change-of-basis matrix M (from the right). This does not change the determinant, if the determinant of M is 1.
The polynomials 
  
    
      
        1
      
    
    {\displaystyle 1}
  , 
  
    
      
        x
        −
        
          x
          
            0
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle x-x_{0}}
  , 
  
    
      
        (
        x
        −
        
          x
          
            0
          
        
        )
        (
        x
        −
        
          x
          
